this gives the approximation obtained by Pratt, where
the risk premium is proportional to the variance of
n. Under risk neutrality, the utility function U(n:) is
linear, the risk premium R is zero, and maximizing
Eq. (2) reduces to maximizing the sum of expected
profit. However, risk aversion means that a2 u;an: 2 <
0 (Pratt, 1964). Then, Eq. (3) implies that the risk premium R increases with the variance of profit. Below,
we will consider the case where m = 3. Going beyond
the variance, this includes the effects of skewness
or downside risk exposure on the risk premium. As
shown by Antle (1987), downside risk aversion means
that a3 u;alf 3 > 0, implying that the third central moment becomes relevant: decision-makers prefer a positive skewness as it reduces their exposure to downside
risk.
