studies were designed to measure com hybrid performance. They measured yield and grain moisture for a
range of com hybrids. Because other inputs (including
cultural practices) were uniformly administrated during the experiment at each site, yield variations in each
location are mainly due to the choice of hybrid maturity, genetic improvements and uncontrollable factors (mainly weather effects). This provides a basis
for evaluating the evolution of the distribution of corn
yield and cost over time and across space.
Table 1 summarizes the data for the three research
stations. Number of observations (N), average growing degree days (GDD)4 and its standard deviation,
average yield (bushel/acre), average corn moisture at
harvest (%) and the range of RM for each location are
presented. As expected, as one moves north, average
GDD declines. Below, we will examine the evolution
of GDD as a proxy measure of climate change. The
average yield over the sample period decreases as one
moves north. Relative maturity ranges from 85 to 120
in the south, and from 70 to 110 in the north, reflecting the different climatic conditions.

6. Estimation results
Focusing on the first three central moments of the
distribution of corn yield, com moisture, GDD and
